final_thought: She wondered if the butterflies could feel it too - that terrible disorientation
  when the world changes faster than memory can adapt, when the ancient pathways encoded
  in your bones suddenly lead nowhere.
last_days_scenario: 'Esperanza sits in her empty visitor center, surrounded by faded
  photographs of orange clouds of monarchs that once darkened the sky each winter.
  The last tourists left three weeks ago. Outside, she can hear the distant rumble
  of machinery clearing another hectare for avocado cultivation. Her phone buzzes
  with a message from a researcher in Canada: "Migration route completely disrupted.
  Population down 95%. May be functionally extinct." She sets down the carved butterfly
  her grandmother made, its paint worn smooth by four generations of hands. Tomorrow,
  the bank will foreclose on the sanctuary. Tonight, she''ll walk the empty trails
  one last time, speaking aloud the Purépecha names for each tree, each seasonal marker,
  each sacred site - words that will die with her, just like the butterflies'' ancient
  memory of how to find home.'
